                  <ab type="history">Maala probably evolved from a <date notBefore="1200" notAfter="1299">13th</date>-century hamlet called <placeName ref="LOC2922EndaMa">Ǝndā Masqal</placeName> (later <placeName ref="LOC2908EndaMa">Ǝndā Madḫane ʿAlam</placeName>). It became a town by the
                        <date notBefore="1800" notAfter="1850">early 19th</date> century. Maala
                     grew into a regional centre under <persName ref="PRS10378Yohanne">Yoḥannǝs
                        IV</persName> who chose it for strategic reasons, both commercial (it was
                     located along important trade routes) and political (it was located on the
                     route to Šawā). Maala became an important market town and, in the <date notBefore="1880" notAfter="1889">1880s</date>, the emperor's capital city.
                     However, with the succession of <persName ref="PRS7006Menilek">Mǝnilǝk
                        II</persName>, the political and commercial balance shifted to southern
                        <placeName ref="LOC3010Ethiop">Ethiopia</placeName> in favour of <placeName ref="LOC5597Sawa">Šawā</placeName> and <placeName ref="LOC1216AddisA">ʾAddis
                        ʾAbabā</placeName>. In <date when="1895">1895</date>, Maala was occupied
                     by the Italians and became part of the Colonia Eritrea, but <persName ref="PRS7006Menilek">Mǝnilǝk</persName> reconquered it in <date>January
                        1896</date>. Maala urbanized progressively during the <date notBefore="1900" notAfter="1999">20th</date> century and three particularly
                     important moments can be identified. Under <roleName type="title">daǧǧāzmāč</roleName>
                     <persName ref="PRS1285AbrehaA">ʾAbrǝha ʾArʾayā Dǝmṣu</persName>, new buildings
                     were built, a new Saturday Market was established and various occupational
                     groups were attracted to the town. In the <date notBefore="1920" notAfter="1929">1920s</date> and <date notBefore="1930" notAfter="1939">1930s</date>, the town witnessed an increase in trade activity and
                     modernization of the infrastructure, also thanks to the Italian occupation. In
                     spite of the damages caused by the British air bombardments in
                     <date>September-October 1943</date>, the third wave of urbanization took place between <date when="1942">1942</date>
                     and <date when="1974">1974</date>, including the development of infrastructure, services, commercial
                     activities and administration. The <date notBefore="1974" notAfter="1991">1974-1991</date> war seriously hindered the
                     urbanization process but, after <date when="1991">1991</date>, it has resumed at a great pace. Maala
                     is today the capital of <placeName ref="LOC5932Tegray">Tǝgrāy National Regional
                        State</placeName>. </ab>
               </note>
